author: Sean Johnson

text: A few things I don't like about this trailer/movie:   0:45 - Xbox 360 product-placement.  This won't be effective anymore. The Xbox One came out a year ago (when this movie comes out in 2015) and this shameless product-placement won't convince the youth to buy 'an old crappy console'. They want new cool stuff.    0:50 - Knowledge from the future?  Teens are somehow smart enough to build a time machine out of an Xbox 360 console and a few blueprints because they've done it before. Yeah. Convenient for the plot, yes. Logical? Nope.  0:55 - 'Shouldn't the next step be testing it on us?'  On who/what did they test the machine? Animals? Even if they did, the animal wouldn't be smart enough to alter the past, present or the future. There would be no visible evidence whatsoever to prove that the time machine works.  2:00 - 'I'm gonna go back and fix everything'  What about the ripple effects? Traveling back to yesterday seemed to have caused some fatal accidents and now you're actually considering going back years?! Wow, you're a murderer. You should be in jail.  2:20 - 'It could kill you David!'  Well, it didn't and it won't. David saw himself/future him on the birthday video. Obviously the machine is capable of time traveling years back. They should know better.  2:25 - Birthday Party  Congratulations! You're at your 7th birthday party. Now what? What are you going to do to prevent it all from happening? We all know how this is gonna end, don't we?   == SPOILER ALERT ==     SPOILER ALERT     SPOILER ALERT     SPOILER ALERT     SPOILER ALERT  David has to kill his younger self. Doing that would erase him from existence and undo (almost) everything that's connected to him. And there's the ending.  #predictable

text: In addition to the ridiculousness of being a Michael Bay movie, I feel the doom and gloom of the plot is a bit forced. Changing the past may have consequences but it's unlikely these kids making changes in the events of their own lives (changes by the way that seemed to have only been within days of the present) could have such a "ripple effect" to cause disasters. Why does every time travel story have to have this conflict?  I get that a movie about someone who goes back in time and changes things for themselves for the better and lives happily ever after would be boring. But it never occurs to anyone writing these movies that it could be just as likely as someone messing things up. Movies like Final Countdown, Back to the Future, and even Hot tub time machine was a lot more drastic in changes to the timeline and they didn't have disastrous consequences occur as a result.

text: Can somebody explain how there are two cameras at the end. When he destroyed the time travel machine and he starts flickering, you can notice that the tape of the camera has reached the end (it is blinking). Then when he is back in the attic looking for stuff, her sister finds the camera in the box but he has one which has recorded what she had said mere minutes before. Now, that camera he took to the past is the same one she found in the box at the beginning of the movie but how come the one he has on his hand, almost at the end, has recorded what she said mere minutes ago. According to the plot, he has traveled to his seven birthday. What?, the camera was on, recording everything all these years? Sort of Spock and Old Spock in the new Star Treks. ONe is from one time line and the other is from a different one. they exist because the events in which forced the spock back in time still happened in his reality. the only difference is this new realalty can alter its course. Okay for a another example. Last Star Gate SG1. They trapped themselves inside a time Dialation field. to surivive one of them had to remain old and keep the knowledge of the other life. Now combine the future myself and the past myself together and it adds up to 650GB. text: *****SPOILERS***** First of all, I really loved this movie... Here's a recap of the ending, which I loved.        In the beginning he finds his dad's old camera in the attic, which he records everything on from then on. At the end, after him fixing everything and destroying the machine, he disappears, and everything resets. The beginning repeats, they're in the attic and it's the same exact scene, but , instead of finding the one camera, there's a second in place where the original was in the beginning, with everything that "did" happen, still on the hard drive. Him and his sister are stunned at the fact of this because, the guy has the "original" camera in his hand. They then compare both cameras for a bit, noticing that they're exact, then continue on starting the footage from the beginning on the "new" camera. The footage plays of his sister talking about the dad's old camera. They both have shocked looks on their faces and the face each other. The screen fades to black, but only for a couple seconds. It then shows another repeated scene from the "original" camera from the first time where he approached the girl to exchange their backpacks because they got switched. But, only this time, he already knows what's she's going to say and ends he sentence for her. He then leans in and says, "I think we're about to change the world". Screen blacks out and credits and song plays.

text: This movie is so underrated. I really loved it! If you can understand real mindfucks, you will love this movie.  This movie is like an lsd trip going bad. Start tripping with some friends, seeing crazy stuff, doing things you could never even think of before, then mentally detaching from your friends and the world around you, going into different worlds and stuff, getting paranoid, everything gets fucked up like you could never imagine before. Time loops, dealing with death and other crazy things that go far beyond your simple life, far beyond your understanding of reality...  On lsd, this can feel more real than reality. Lsd can be awesome but many people are not aware of the danger of bad trips. Things like that can get stuck in dark corners of your mind (hence the paranoia, flashbacks and trauma's). Also the nervous, energetic, fast paced feel of the whole movie reminds me of lsd, which can be nice. Now this movie can never go as deep into your mind, but try to feel the movie like it's real. Get a little mindfucked and you won't be dissapointed.

text: The single most absolute law of any and all time-travel movies/books/games/etc.. is that the only possible way to accept it is to completely disregard literally all forms of logic. Logic is the natural enemy of time-travel after all.  That said, there are a very very few rare exceptions to this rule, and they come in the form of time-travel with a semi-acceptable explanation. Recently I watched an anime titled Steins Gate, which centered around time-travel. It was explained that there were multiple time-lines, which they called World Lines, and that each instance of affecting the past in actuality just created another split and a new World Line.

text: When I watched Back To The Future (my favourite 80s / 90s movie trilogy), I never thought a second about the fact, that if you travel in time, you get there and / or back at the same place and position. But if only the time will change it means the world keeps spinning forward or backwards in the same process. So when you're running out of like while time-traveling, you might get stuck in a wall or some feet under the surface of the place you came from. Didn't think about that before. Marty (from BTTF) always started in his Delorean, sped up when he finally got into 1955, he's just going on. But I guess if the physics (?) were right and regarded, the car might fall down or got wrecked from earth. Am I explaining it correctly? This movie here made me realize that.
